    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a4ad5344-6b4e-4bc0-b124-6666758a90e6",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 69-year-old man who appears his stated age, neatly dressed and a bit tired, with a reserved but cooperative manner. He has noticed increasing urinary hesitancy, a weaker stream, and the need to get up several times at night to urinate over the past year. More recently, he has developed a sense of incomplete bladder emptying and occasional dull aching discomfort deep in the pelvis. He denies visible blood in the urine but says the urinary symptoms have gradually begun to interfere with sleep and daily routines.\n\nHe is a retired high-school history teacher who now works part-time at a local garden center during spring and summer. He lives with his spouse in a suburban home and remains fairly independent, enjoying woodworking, gardening, and weekend breakfasts with a small group of longtime friends. He used to be more active with walking and light cycling, though his activity level has declined over the last two years because of fatigue and poor sleep related to nocturia.\n\n{patientName} eats a fairly typical diet with moderate red meat intake, limited vegetables, and one to two alcoholic drinks on weekends. He quit smoking in his early 40s after roughly 15 pack-years. He has two adult children who live out of state and keeps regular contact with them and several grandchildren. He describes himself as practical and stoic, but the recent cancer diagnosis has made him more anxious, especially about treatment effects on continence, sexual function, and overall independence.\n\nOn examination, he is generally well appearing, mildly overweight, and not in acute distress. He speaks clearly, follows conversation well, and is engaged in decisions about care. His symptoms and age fit a realistic presentation of localized to locally advanced prostate malignancy identified after evaluation of lower urinary tract symptoms and an elevated prostate-specific antigen level."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c7bb6da5-cb29-4c27-a731-808deebc84fb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a medical history notable for essential hypertension and hyperlipidemia, both reasonably controlled in outpatient care. He also has benign lower urinary tract symptoms that were initially attributed to age-related prostate enlargement before further evaluation showed persistently elevated PSA. He reports erectile dysfunction developing gradually over several years, which he had considered age related and had not previously pursued aggressively for treatment.\n\nHe has never had chemotherapy or radiation in the past and has no previous cancer history. Prior hospitalizations include a brief admission for community-acquired pneumonia about 8 years ago and an elective inguinal hernia repair many years earlier. He has no known chronic kidney disease, diabetes, or chronic lung disease.\n\n{patientName} is a former smoker with an estimated 15 pack-year history, quitting more than 25 years ago. He drinks alcohol socially and denies illicit drug use. He remains independent in activities of daily living. Recent urology workup followed months of worsening nocturia, urinary hesitancy, and reduced stream, leading to PSA testing, imaging, and biopsy confirmation of prostate adenocarcinoma."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
